fields.descriptive_line:
Board game with box of playing pieces, made in the USA by Parker Brothers in 1933. The game includes a board, metal plane pieces, metal boat pieces, two sets of game-play cards, an instruction sheet and an advert for Monopoly. 
[Board] Board for 'Henrik Van Loon's Wide World Game', made in the USA by the Parker Brothers in 1933.
[Box Base] Card box base for 'Hendrik Van Loon's Wide World Game' pieces.
[Box Lid] Card box lid for 'Hendrik Van Loon's Wide World Game' pieces.
[Pale Green Box Compartment] Pale green card box compartment.
[Blue Box Compartment] Blue card box compartment.
[Red Box Compartment] Red card compartment for the box of pieces.
[Yellow Box Compartment] Yellow card compartment for a box
[Plane Pieces] Four metal plane pieces, coloured red, yellow, green and blue.
[Boat Pieces] Four metal boat playing pieces, coloured red, yellow, green and blue.
[Instruction Booklet] Printed instruction booklet with red and black font. 
[Monopoly Advert] Small paper advertising booklet for other games by the Parker Brothers.
[Wide World Ticket] Printed yellow 'Wide World Ticket'.
[Green Game Card] Green cards with instructions for game play on them, such as 'GOOD WEATHER: STEAM AHEAD 3 DOTS'.
[Pink Game Card] Pink cards printed with black ink instructions on game play for the players. One example is 'FLY TO THIRD CITY AHEAD'.
fields.physical_description:
The set is, at its most contained level, a box of pieces (made from card) and a board (made from thicker card). Contained in the box are the game-play metal pieces and cards, an advert for Monopoly, and several pieces of card that divide the box into sections.
[Board] When the board is folded in half, the exterior is dark gold in colour, with significant markings to the colour. On one side of the folded section is a title sheet, with the name of the game and a picture of a mountain. It is also signed by the Parker Brothers. When unfolded, the image on the board is of a world map (minus the Pacific Ocean). It is shaded mainly in orange to indicate where deserts and mountain ranges are, and green for everywhere else. The sea is white. There are some features drawn onto the sea, such as boats and giant fish. On the top left-hand corner there is an image of night, while day is visible on the other side. There is a 'desert island' motif along the bottom of the board. The paths that the players must follow are black dashed lines with black spots along. 
[Box Base] Card box base with cream exterior and plain interior. Rectangle in shape, and designed to hold the pieces for the board game.
[Box Lid] Card box lid wrapped in paper, which displays the name of the game and a picture of a mountain, identical to the motif featured on the board when folded. 
[Pale Green Box Compartment] Pale green card folded to act as a compartment in the pieces box. Each corner is split so the compartment can be laid flat if required. While the outside is green, the inside has not been coloured. 
[Blue Box Compartment] Piece of card that is blue on one side and plain on the other. The long, rectangular piece of card has been folded in three places to ensure that it can be folded once inside the box to form a compartment.
[Red Box Compartment] Rectangular piece of red card (red on one side, plain on the other), that has been folded four times in order to make it into a compartment. 
[Yellow Box Compartment] Piece of card, yellow on one side, plain on the other. There are four large holes pierced into the card, in order for pieces to be placed into it. The card has been cut and folded four times so that it can be laid flat if required.
[Plane Pieces] Metal plane playing pieces, each coloured a different colour. The planes are each moulded to a small stand.
[Boat Pieces] Moulded metal into a battleship shape, each painted a different colour. The base remains unpainted.
[Instruction Booklet] White paper printed with red and black ink with the instructions of how to play the game. There are drawings included, and the paper is folded in two to form a booklet.
[Monopoly Advert] White paper with black printing advertising games and toys by Parker Brothers. There are photographs included and Monopoly is the game included on the front.
[Wide World Ticket] Black printing onto yellow card, detailing a passage from San Francisco to Manila. The ticket is rectangular in shape and there are six included. 
[Green Game Card] Green card printed on both sides. One side is printed in black with a task or order for the player to complete, the reverse is printed in black a boat and the name of the game. 
[Pink Game Card] Pink cards printed on one side with short tasks or orders for players to complete in black ink, and on the other with a picture of a plane and the name of the game in black ink.

fields.title: Hendrik Van Loon's Wide World Game
fields.history_note:
The game was made in the USA by Parker Brothers in 1933. Parker Brothers was one of the foremost American games manufacturers of the twentieth century. It is now a subsidiary of Hasbro. The company was founded by George Parker in the 1880s and he was later joined by his two brothers.
Hendrik Willem Van Loon (1882-1944) wrote many books, illustrating them himself. One of the best known is The Story of Mankind, a history of the world for children, which won the first Newbery Medal in 1922.
George Parker met Van Loon at the Essex Institute in  Salem Massachusetts and this resulted in Parker Brothers  producing a travel game using Van Loon’s name. he also  provided the illustration of the world used in the game.
The company continued to make the game but later  dropped the Van Loon name. This example is one of the  earliest produced and is in remakably good condition.
